        		<marginalia hand="Italian">
        			<language ident="LA">
            			<position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    				<marginalia_text>
                    					Nescia Virtus Stare Loco. Nescia Ars edere 
                      			 </marginalia_text>
                      			 <X-ref book_title="Pharsalia" language="LA" person="Lucan" text="Nescia virtus stare loco"/>
            			 </position>
        				<position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
        					<marginalia_text>
        						Loco. Ars quò penetrantior, eò
        					</marginalia_text>
        				</position>
        				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
        					<marginalia_text>
        						/ mora[e] impatientior.
        					</marginalia_text>
        				</position>
        				<position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
        					<marginalia_text>
        						) Vt in primis Ars Ca[e]sariana, Sallustiana, 
        					</marginalia_text>
        					<person name="Julius Caesar"/>
        					<person name="Sallust"/>
        				</position>
        				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
        					<marginalia_text>
        						) Tacitana.		 
        					</marginalia_text>
        					<person name="Tacitus"/>
        				</position>
        				<position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
        					<marginalia_text>
        						Cui ) finitima Virgiliana in Aneide;	 
        						Ouidiana in Metamorphosi;
        						) Senecana in			 
        					</marginalia_text>
        					<person name="Virgil"/>
        					<person name="Ovid"/>
        					<person name="Seneca"/>
        					<book title="Aeneid"/>
        					<book title="Metamorphoses"/>
        				</position>
        				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
        					<marginalia_text>
        						Traga[e]dijs. Tam facilè fluentissima, quàm maxime omnium neruosa prudentia. 
        					</marginalia_text> 
        					<book title="Seneca's Tragedies"/>
        				</position>
        				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
        					<marginalia_text>
        						Ô argumentosum iudicium. Ô diuina, et alata
        						sententiarum Celeritas. Solus stilus adamantinus.
        					</marginalia_text>
        					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
        				</position>
        			</language>
        			<translation>
        				"The virtue of being unable to stay in one place." The art of being unable to produce in one place.	<!-- CG: I am not confident about this. The first sentence is taken from Lucan, and I tried to have it make sense here. --><!--JG: I'll just send it to the group so that other people can have a look at it. This is a tricky passage-->
        				The more penetrating the art, the more intolerant of delay, especially like the art of Caesar, Sallust, Tacitus.
        				To which the related art of Virgil in the Aeneid, Ovid in the Metamorphosis, Seneca in the Tragedies.
        				Art is as readily flowing, as prudence is the most vigorous of all things. 
        				O judgment rich in proof. O divine and winged speed of thoughts. Only an adamantine style.
        			</translation>
        		</marginalia>
