    		<marginalia book_id="FolgersHa2" hand="Italian" id="Ha2.017r_0001" marginalia_continues_to="Ha2.016v_0001" marginalia_to_transcription="Ha2.016v.xml">
    			<language ident="LA">
    				<position book_orientation="270" place="left_margin">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						Hic superat ipsu[m] Ca[e]sarem, et Maronem. Cedant ipse Crispus, ( [p. 352: Tacitus, Paterculus, Naso huic Eutrapelo. Quicu[m] suo Eunapio, Juliano,
    						Philostrato, non modò suis Romanis = = singularis est artifex argumentosi, facillimè fluentis, exquisiti styli.]
    						<!-- Continues onto facing page, right margin, Ha2.016v. --> 
    					</marginalia_text>
    					<person name="Julius Caesar"/>
    					<person name="Virgil"/>    					
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				This man surpasses Caesar himself, and Virgil. Crispus himself [p. 352: Tacitus, Paterculus, and Ovid yield to this Eutrapelus. With his Eunapius, Julian, and Philostratus, not only with his Romans,
    				he is a singular author of an exquisite style, rich in argument and most readily flowing.]
    			</translation>
